Many incidents involving [[double taxation]] arose from liability to duty in different provinces, as well as other jurisdictions abroad, which were dealt with inconsistently among the provinces.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Goodman|first= Wolfe D.|date= 1974|title= International and Interprovincial Death Duty and Gift Tax Problems|url= http://digitalcommons.osgoode.yorku.ca/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2599&context=ohlj|journal= [[Osgoode Hall Law Journal]]|volume= 12|issue= 1|pages= 191{{en dash}}205|ref=harv}}</ref>

===Collection in Ontario===
[[Image:Mitch Hepburn.jpg|thumb|right|[[Mitchell Hepburn]], Premier and Treasurer of Ontario in the 1930s]]
[[Image:John Rudolphus Booth.jpg|thumb|right|[[John Rudolphus Booth]], whose estate was Hepburn's principal target]]
Ontario was especially notable in its pursuit of duties. [[Mitchell Hepburn]], in his capacity as [[Treasurer of Ontario]], adopted a more aggressive approach in their collection on large estates, which resulted in millions of dollars in extra government revenues.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mitchell F. Hepburn, Ontario ex-premier dies|pages = 1, 3|newspaper= [[Toronto Daily Star]]|date= January 5, 1953}}</ref> He made no apologies for doing so, as he noted in a speech in 1938.<ref>{{cite speech |title=Present Day Problems |author=Mitchell Hepburn |date=December 15, 1938 |location=[[Empire Club of Canada]] |url=http://speeches.empireclub.org/60541/data?n=1 |accessdate=October 6, 2013 }}</ref>

In 1937, legislation was passed that allowed for reexamination of estates for deaths that had occurred back to the beginning of 1916, and also included many gifts ''[[inter vivos]]'' within the duty's scope.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title = The Succession Duty Amendment Act, 1937|abbr = S.O.|year = 1937|chapter = 3|link = https://archive.org/stream/statutesofprovin1937onta#page/8/mode/2up|linkloc = archive.org}}</ref> Hepburn consequently ordered that all files relating to estates worth $500,000 or more, together with those of smaller estates where evasion was suspected, were to be reopened, with the expectation of raising further duties anywhere from $70 million to $100 million.<ref name="McEachernFP1938">{{cite news |title=Ontario's Death Duty Inquisition|first = R.A.|last= McEachern|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PWg_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=7lMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4168,578348&dq=hepburn+succession+duty+g:loccanada&hl=en|newspaper= [[Financial Post]]|date= January 22, 1938|pages = 11{{endash}}12|accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> The collection tactics employed included the seizure of books and records without a warrant, different methods for valuing assets, and the assessment of penalties that could amount to double or triple the amount of the duty involved.<ref name="McEachernFP1938"/>

One estate of particular focus in this campaign was that of the late [[John Rudolphus Booth]], who had died in 1925. Although succession duties of $4.28 million were paid in 1927,<ref>{{cite news |title= Claims Booth Duties Paid|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KplTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QzgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1208,1689121&dq=booth+succession+duty+g:loccanada&hl=en|newspaper= [[Regina Leader-Post]]|date= September 18, 1937|accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> Hepburn subsequently claimed more in 1937.<ref>{{cite news |title= Ontario Assembly Prorogues Today|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UXctAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6552,331650&dq=hepburn+succession+duty+act+amendment+g:loccanada&hl=en|newspaper= [[Montreal Gazette]]|date= December 3, 1937|accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> Booth's heirs eventually paid another $3 million in 1939.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ottawa Estates Pay Additional Duties to Govt.|url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ZvIuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vNsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7028,1797999&dq=booth+succession+duty+g:loccanada&hl=en|newspaper= [[Ottawa Citizen]]|date= September 23, 1939|accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref>

===Where succession duty could apply===
Duty cannot be charged where property is left outside the province to beneficiaries who are neither resident nor domiciled in the province.<ref>{{cite BAILII|litigants=Charles S. Cotton and another v The King|link=|court=UKPC|format=1|year=1913|num=56|parallelcite=[1914] AC 176; (1913), 15 DLR 283 (PC)|date=11 November 1913|courtname=[[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|P.C.]]|juris=Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite BAILII|litigants=The Provincial Treasurer of Alberta and another v Clara E. Kerr and another|link=|court=UKPC|format=1|year=1933|num=57|parallelcite=[1933] AC 710; [1933] 4 DLR 81 (PC)|date=27 July 1933|courtname=[[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|P.C.]]|juris=Alberta}}</ref> Taken as a whole, chargeability to succession duty depended upon whether the donor's domicile, the donee's residence, as well as the donee's status at the date of the deceased's death and the date of the disposition of the estate. In 1967, Ontario published a table outlining the various effects:

