==Conversion to deemed dispositions for capital gains tax (after 1971)==
Upon the repeal of the federal estate and gift taxes on January 1, 1972, the income tax régime was altered to provide for a [[capital gains tax]], which included liability arising from the "deemed disposition" of assets. Liability will arise from gifts from,<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =Income Tax Act|abbr =R.S.C.|year =1985 (5th Supp.)|chapter =1|section =69|subsection =1|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/I-3.3/section-69.html}}</ref> and the death of,<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =Income Tax Act|abbr =R.S.C.|year =1985 (5th Supp.)|chapter =1|section =70|subsection =5|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/I-3.3/section-70.html}}</ref> the taxpayer, as well in the following circumstances:

:* the use of a property has changed<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =Income Tax Act|abbr =R.S.C.|year =1985 (5th Supp.)|chapter =1|section =45|subsection =1|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/I-3.3/section-45.html}}</ref>
:* the taxpayer emigrates from Canada<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =Income Tax Act|abbr =R.S.C.|year =1985 (5th Supp.)|chapter =1|section =128.1|subsection =1|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/I-3.3/section-128.1.html}}</ref>
:* a trust for a taxpayer's spouse or common-law partner, when that beneficiary dies, or on the 21st anniversary of a trust<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =Income Tax Act|abbr =R.S.C.|year =1985 (5th Supp.)|chapter =1|section =104|subsection =4|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/I-3.3/section-104.html}}</ref>

==Recent conversion of provincial probate fees into probate taxes==
The provinces have moved in recent years to convert fees for the granting of [[probate|letters probate]] and [[letters of administration]] from [[flat rate]]s to ones based on the value of the estate. In 1992, Ontario introduced fees at a level higher than in any other province.<ref>O.Reg. 293/92</ref> The [[Supreme Court of Canada]] declared that the method by which it was introduced was unconstitutional, as its basis had not been the subject of appropriate legislation.<ref>{{cite CanLII|litigants=Re Eurig Estate|link=|year=1998|court=scc|num=801|format=canlii|parallelcite=[1998] 2 SCR 565|date=1998-10-22}}</ref>

As a result, the provinces{{efn|with the exception of Quebec, which never had such a regime}} passed legislation to legitimate the fees already in effect:

