{{Infobox person | name = Rudolf Callmann | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1892|9|29|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Cologne]], [[Rhine Province|Rhenish Prussia]], [[Germany]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1976|3|12|1892|9|29|df=y}} | death_place = [[Kew Gardens, Queens]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] | nationality = [[German American]] | other_names = | known_for = | spouse = {{Marriage|Maria Hess|1919}} | children = {{Interlanguage link multi|Ellen Callmann|de}} | occupation = Legal scholar }}
'''Rudolf Callmann''' (29 September 1892 – 12 March 1976<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/03/15/archives/rudolph-callmann-83-dies-lawyer-aided-jewish-refugees.html |title=Rudolph Callmann, 83, Dies; Lawyer Aided Jewish Refugees |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=15 March 1976 }}</ref>) was a [[German American]] legal scholar. He was preeminent in the field of German and American [[competition law]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Baums |first=Theodor |chapter=Rechtsnorm und richterliche Entscheidung im Wettbewerbsrecht – Der Beitrag Rudolf Callmanns zur deutschen und amerikanischen Rechtsentwicklung |title=Der Einfluß deutscher Emigranten auf die Rechtsentwicklung in den USA und in Deutschland |editor-last=Lutter |editor-first=Marcus |year=1993 |location=Tübingen |publisher=Mohr |isbn=3-16-146080-4 |pages=63–84 |language=de}}</ref>
Born in [[Cologne]] into a wealthy [[Ashkenazi Jew|Jewish]] family, Callmann earned a [[doctorate]] in law from the [[University of Freiburg]] in 1919. His studies had been interrupted by frontline service in [[World War I]]. In 1923, he entered his father's law firm in Cologne, and established himself as a leading authority on [[unfair competition]] and [[antitrust law]]. As a [[German Jewish military personnel of World War I|World War I veteran]] he was [[Anti-Jewish legislation in prewar Nazi Germany|allowed]] to practice even after the [[Machtergreifung]] in 1933, but in 1936 decided to emigrate to the [[United States]]. He was offered a research fellowship at [[Harvard Law School]], where he worked with [[Zechariah Chafee]], while getting accustomed to American [[common law]], and in 1939 he passed the [[bar exam]]. Between 1939 and 1945 he completed the American edition of his [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]] on unfair competition, now (in revised edition) known as ''Callmann on Unfair Competition, Trademarks, and Monopolies''.
In 1949, Callmann founded the [[boutique law firm]] [[Greene, Callmann & Durr]] in [[New York City]], along with Orville N. Greene (1908–1997) and Frank L. Durr (1904–1990), where he practiced until 1971.
