'''Spoofing''', or '''decoying''', is the practice of inundating online networks with bogus or incomplete [[Computer file|files]] of the same name in an effort to reduce [[copyright infringement]] on [[file sharing]] networks.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/new_media/2093931.stm Record industry 'spoofs' net pirates], BBC News. 4 July 2002.</ref><ref>Chartrand, Sabra. [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/17/technology/17patent.html?pagewanted=1 New Way to Combat Online Piracy], ''New York Times''. May 17, 2004.</ref> [[Cary Sherman]], president of the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), calls spoofing "an appropriate response to the problem of peer-to-peer piracy," and "a self-help measure that is completely lawful."<ref>Murray, Brian H. ''Defending the Brand: Aggressive Strategies for Protecting Your Brand in the Online Arena'', AMACOM, pg. 119, October 31, 2003.</ref>
